label.value: Union for International Cancer Control Stage

value.value: Cancer staging defined according to the criteria set by the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC).
The M (metastasis) category value associated with cancer staging data that was determined according to the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC) clinical staging criteria.
The N (lymph node involvement) category value associated with cancer staging data that was determined according to the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC) clinical staging criteria.
A cancer stage defined according to the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC) clinical staging criteria.
Any tissue from a human fetus.
The T (primary tumor extent) category value associated with cancer staging data that was determined according to the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC) clinical staging criteria.
An objective classification system use to document and track the development of breasts in female children during puberty.
Only the papilla is elevated above the level of the chest wall.
Elevation of the breasts and papillae may occur as small mounds along with some increased diameter of the areolae.
The M (metastasis) category value associated with cancer staging data that was determined according to the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC) pathologic staging criteria.
The breasts and areolae continue to enlarge, although they show no separation of contour.
The areolae and papillae elevate above the level of the breasts and form secondary mounds with further development of the overall breast tissue.
Mature female breasts have developed. The papillae may extend slightly above the contour of the breasts as the result of the recession of the areolae.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Scale in Females

value.value: An objective classification system use to document and track the development of pubic hair in female children during puberty.

A molecular biology device that utilizes a set of defined oligonucleotide probes, recombinant clones, or other samples attached in a specific grid arrangement to a solid support for nucleic acid hybridization assays in gene mapping studies or in determining gene sequences, sequence variations, or gene expression patterns.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 1, Female

value.value: Vellus hair develops over the pubes in a manner not greater than that over the anterior wall. There is no sexual hair.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 2, Female

value.value: Sparse, long, pigmented, downy hair, which is straight or only slightly curled, appears. These hairs are seen mainly along the labia. This stage is difficult to quantitate on black and white photographs, particularly when pictures are of fair-haired subjects.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 3, Female

value.value: Considerably darker, coarser, and curlier sexual hair appears. The hair has now spread sparsely over the junction of the pubes.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 4, Female

value.value: The hair distribution is adult in type but decreased in total quantity. There is no spread to the medial surface of the thighs.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 5, Female

value.value: Hair is adult in quantity and type and appears to have an inverse triangle of the classically feminine type. There is spread to the medial surface of the thighs but not above the base of the inverse triangle.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Scale in Males

value.value: An objective classification system use to document and track the development of pubic hair in male children during puberty.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 1, Male

value.value: Vellus hair appears over the pubes with a degree of development similar to that over the abdominal wall. There is no androgen-sensitive pubic hair.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 2, Male

value.value: There is sparse development of long pigmented downy hair, which is only slightly curled or straight. The hair is seen chiefly at the base of penis. This stage may be difficult to evaluate on a photograph, especially if the subject has fair hair.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 3, Male

value.value: The pubic hair is considerably darker, coarser, and curlier. The distribution is now spread over the junction of the pubes, and at this point that hair may be recognized easily on black and white photographs.
The N (lymph node involvement) category value associated with cancer staging data that was determined according to the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC) pathologic staging criteria.
Any of a number of technologies that permits the visualization and acquisition of images into a physical or electronic record.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 4, Male

value.value: The hair distribution is now adult in type but still is considerably less that seen in adults. There is no spread to the medial surface of the thighs.

label.value: Tanner Pubic Hair Development Stage 5, Male

value.value: Hair distribution is adult in quantity and type and is described in the inverse triangle. There can be spread to the medial surface of the thighs.

label.value: Tanner Genitalia Development Scale in Males

value.value: An objective classification system use to document and track external genital development in male children during puberty.
The testes, scrotal sac, and penis have a size and proportion similar to those seen in early childhood.

There is enlargement of the scrotum and testes and a change in the texture of the scrotal skin. The scrotal skin may also be reddened, a finding not obvious when viewed on a black and white photograph.
Further growth of the penis has occurred, initially in length, although with some increase in circumference. There also is increased growth of the testes and scrotum.

The penis is significantly enlarged in length and circumference, with further development of the glans penis. The testes and scrotum continue to enlarge, and there is distinct darkening of the scrotal skin. This is difficult to evaluate on a black-and-white photograph.
The genitalia are adult with regard to size and shape.
An objective classification system use to document and track testicular development in male children during puberty.
Testicular volume < 4 mL or long axis < 2.5 cm.
Develop and evaluate strategies that will enhance, restore, and/or maintain the immune systems of HIV-infected individuals and extend our understanding of immunopathogenesis.
Testicular volume 4-8 mL (or 2.5 to 3.3 cm long).
Testicular volume 9-12 mL (or 3.4 to 4.0 cm long).
Testicular volume 15-20 mL (or 4.1 to 4.5 cm long).
Testicular volume > 20 mL (or > 4.5 cm long).
